590
01:18:18,520 --> 01:18:26,900
He started down the road to their house, then
stopped after a few steps. He suddenly saw

591
01:18:26,900 --> 01:18:35,950
himself, and his life, in the clear light
of day. He was a poor man, planning to leave

592
01:18:35,950 --> 01:18:44,020
his sickly wife all alone and without money.
And how was he planning to do this heartless

593
01:18:44,020 --> 01:18:54,160
thing? By telling lies to two kind people
who felt sorry for him.

594
01:18:54,160 --> 01:19:12,140
He turned and walked slowly back to the farm.

595
01:19:12,140 --> 01:19:14,400
CHAPTER SEVEN

596
01:19:14,400 --> 01:19:17,900
The last ride

597
01:19:17,900 --> 01:19:27,110
It was about midday when Ethan got home. Zeena
was by the fire with a scarf on her head and

598
01:19:27,110 --> 01:19:34,020
a book about stomach pains in her hand. She
did not move or look up.

599
01:19:34,020 --> 01:19:38,480
'Where's Mattie?' Ethan asked.

600
01:19:38,480 --> 01:19:47,690
Zeena continued to read her book. 'I guess
she's packing her case,' she replied.

601
01:19:47,690 --> 01:19:58,170
Ethan went straight upstairs. Mattie's door
was closed. 'Matt,' he said in a low voice.

602
01:19:58,170 --> 01:20:04,690
There was no answer, so he gently pushed open
the door.

603
01:20:04,690 --> 01:20:11,980
Mattie was sitting on her case in her best
dress, with her back to the door and her face

604
01:20:11,980 --> 01:20:20,160
in her hands. She was crying. Ethan put his
hands on her shoulders.

605
01:20:20,160 --> 01:20:26,760
'Matt - oh, don't - oh, Matt!'

606
01:20:26,760 --> 01:20:36,770
'Ethan - I thought you weren't coming back!'
she cried, lifting her wet face to his.

607
01:20:36,770 --> 01:20:45,360
He took her in his arms, and kissed her soft
hair. Then they heard Zeena calling, and moved

608
01:20:45,360 --> 01:20:48,790
away from each other.

609
01:20:48,790 --> 01:20:56,100
He carried her suitcase downstairs, and with
every 'tick' of the clock, the pain in his

610
01:20:56,100 --> 01:20:59,440
heart grew.

611
01:20:59,440 --> 01:21:08,400
At dinner, he could eat nothing. After the
meal, Zeena sat down by the fire and Mattie

612
01:21:08,400 --> 01:21:16,250
began to wash the dishes, Jotham got up from
the table and asked Ethan:

613
01:21:16,250 --> 01:21:21,170
'So what time will I come round for Mattie?'

614
01:21:21,170 --> 01:21:28,690
'You needn't come round; I'm going to drive
her over myself,' he answered.

615
01:21:28,690 --> 01:21:35,900
Zeena lifted her head. 'I want you here this
afternoon, Ethan. You'll have to get the room

616
01:21:35,900 --> 01:21:40,970
ready for the new girl. Jotham can take Mattie.'

617
01:21:40,970 --> 01:21:50,801
'I'm going to drive her over myself,' he repeated
in a hard voice. He turned to Mattie: 'You

618
01:21:50,801 --> 01:21:57,420
be ready at three, Matt. I've got business
in Corbury.'

619
01:21:57,420 --> 01:22:04,650
With those words, he left the house. He could
feel the hot blood beating in his head, as

620
01:22:04,650 --> 01:22:14,250
the anger burned inside him. He hurried through
his work, then went to get the horse and sleigh.

621
01:22:14,250 --> 01:22:19,400
He remembered the day when he had got the
sleigh ready in order to fetch his wife's

622
01:22:19,400 --> 01:22:28,130
cousin from the station. It was little more
than a year ago, on a soft afternoon just

623
01:22:28,130 --> 01:22:36,630
like this, with a whisper of spring in the
air. And all the days between then and now

624
01:22:36,630 --> 01:22:41,380
came back to him, one by one.

625
01:22:41,380 --> 01:22:49,020
He jumped into the sleigh and drove up to
the house. The kitchen was empty, and Mattie's

626
01:22:49,020 --> 01:22:57,630
case and coat lay ready by the door. After
a moment, he heard someone moving about in

627
01:22:57,630 --> 01:23:05,610
his study-room. He pushed open the door and
saw Mattie standing by the table.

628
01:23:05,610 --> 01:23:09,750
'What are you doing in there, Matt?'

629
01:23:09,750 --> 01:23:13,690
'Just looking round,' she replied.

630
01:23:13,690 --> 01:23:16,250
'Where's Zeena?'

631
01:23:16,250 --> 01:23:22,610
'Gone upstairs. She said she had her pains
again.'

632
01:23:22,610 --> 01:23:24,750
'Didn't she say goodbye?'

633
01:23:24,750 --> 01:23:30,060
'No. That was all she said.'

634
01:23:30,060 --> 01:23:37,710
They went back into the kitchen. Ethan looked
slowly around the room, thinking, 'In a few

635
01:23:37,710 --> 01:23:47,831
hours I shall return here alone. I'm looking
at Mattie here for the last time.' He could

636
01:23:47,831 --> 01:23:52,690
not believe it; it all seemed so unreal.

637
01:23:52,690 --> 01:24:04,210
'Come on,' he said, opening the door. He helped
her into the sleigh, and with a 'Go along!'

638
01:24:04,210 --> 01:24:09,010
to the horse, they started off down the hill.

639
01:24:09,010 --> 01:24:19,650
'We got lots of time for a good ride, Matt!'
he said, taking her hand in his.

640
01:24:19,650 --> 01:24:26,480
As they left the farm, he did not take the
road towards Starkfield, but turned the horse

641
01:24:26,480 --> 01:24:33,950
to the light, up the Bettsbridge road. Mattie
did not seem surprised.

642
01:24:33,950 --> 01:24:38,170
'Are you going round by Shadow Pond?'

643
01:24:38,170 --> 01:24:44,130
'You knew, didn't you?' he laughed.

644
01:24:44,130 --> 01:24:51,580
The road took them down into a wood, where
the trees shone reddish in the afternoon sun,

645
01:24:51,580 --> 01:25:00,250
leaving soft blue shadows on the untouched
snow. There was a warm stillness in the wood.

646
01:25:00,250 --> 01:25:12,130
In the middle was a small icy pond, with sweet-smelling
trees all around. It was a quiet, secret place,

647
01:25:12,130 --> 01:25:21,650
like the quiet sadness in Ethan's heart. They
saw a fallen tree by the icy water, half covered

648
01:25:21,650 --> 01:25:30,170
in snow. It was where they had sat once last
August, together with a group of young people

649
01:25:30,170 --> 01:25:34,170
from Starkfield church.

650
01:25:34,170 --> 01:25:43,830
They sat down now in the same place, and remembered
those few happy moments from that hot summer

651
01:25:43,830 --> 01:25:52,580
afternoon. Ethan looked at Mattie's hair,
and wished he could touch it again. He wanted

652
01:25:52,580 --> 01:26:00,370
to tell her that it smelled of the woods in
springtime, but he had never learned to say

653
01:26:00,370 --> 01:26:03,560
things like that.

654
01:26:03,560 --> 01:26:12,540
When the sun began to go down behind the hill,
Mattie said: 'We mustn't stay here any longer.'

655
01:26:12,540 --> 01:26:20,830
As they drove back towards Starkfield, the
sky was turning grey, with a cold red over

656
01:26:20,830 --> 01:26:23,230
the western hills.

657
01:26:23,230 --> 01:26:32,630
'Matt,' Ethan said at last. 'What'll you do?
Can't you ask your father's family for help?'

658
01:26:32,630 --> 01:26:44,130
'I don't want to ask them,' she replied, then
after a moment added: 'I guess I'll find something.'

659
01:26:44,130 --> 01:26:46,920
'You know I'd do anything for you -'

660
01:26:46,920 --> 01:26:49,500
'Yes, I know.'

661
01:26:49,500 --> 01:26:53,570
'But I can't -'

662
01:26:53,570 --> 01:27:04,310
She was silent, but he felt her shoulder shaking.
'Oh, Matt,' he cried. 'I wish...'

663
01:27:04,310 --> 01:27:14,580
She turned to him. 'Ethan, I found this.'
She held out a piece of paper. It was the

664
01:27:14,580 --> 01:27:22,530
unfinished letter to his wife, which he had
forgotten to destroy. A painful happiness

665
01:27:22,530 --> 01:27:32,180
ran through him. Were Mattie's dreams the
same as his? He had to know. 'Do you feel

666
01:27:32,180 --> 01:27:37,650
like that too, Matt? Tell me, Matt, tell me!'

667
01:27:37,650 --> 01:27:47,210
'Oh, Ethan, what does it matter now?' she
cried. With a sudden movement, she tore the

668
01:27:47,210 --> 01:27:56,330
letter into pieces and threw them onto the
snow. For a moment, she was silent, then said

669
01:27:56,330 --> 01:27:58,030
in a low voice:

670
01:27:58,030 --> 01:28:07,100
'The first time I thought of you like that
was at Shadow Pond. Then I often used to think

671
01:28:07,100 --> 01:28:15,760
about you on summer nights when the moon was
too bright and I couldn't sleep.'

672
01:28:15,760 --> 01:28:24,510
Her words filled Ethan's heart with sweetness.
Darkness began to fall and they drove on in

673
01:28:24,510 --> 01:28:28,430
silence for a while.

674
01:28:28,430 --> 01:28:37,860
'I'm fastened hand and foot, Matt. There isn't
a thing I can do,' he began again.

675
01:28:37,860 --> 01:28:41,620
'You must write to me sometimes, Ethan.'

676
01:28:41,620 --> 01:28:49,550
'Oh, what can writing do? I want to put my
hand out and touch you. I want to take care

677
01:28:49,550 --> 01:28:54,700
of you. I want to be there when you're sick
and when you're lonely.'

678
01:28:54,700 --> 01:29:02,570
'Oh, Ethan, I wish I was dead!' she cried.

679
01:29:02,570 --> 01:29:08,150
'Don't let's talk that way,' he whispered.

680
01:29:08,150 --> 01:29:14,820
As they arrived in Starkfield, a sleigh with
bells passed them. They heard happy children's

681
01:29:14,820 --> 01:29:22,860
voices and saw a group of village boys with
sleds. They drove on to the top of the Corbury

682
01:29:22,860 --> 01:29:30,320
road. On one side was the tall white shape
of the church, on the other were the dark

683
01:29:30,320 --> 01:29:39,930
shadows of the Varnum trees. The steep slope
lay empty and white below them. An idea came

684
01:29:39,930 --> 01:29:49,270
to Ethan, to help himself and her through
their miserable last hour. He turned to Mattie.

685
01:29:49,270 --> 01:29:57,520
'We never went coasting last night. Shall
we go down now? How would you like that?'

686
01:29:57,520 --> 01:29:59,930
'There isn't time!'

687
01:29:59,930 --> 01:30:09,070
'There's as much time as we want,' he said.
'The hired girl can wait. Lock, someone's

688
01:30:09,070 --> 01:30:12,690
left a sled under the trees.'

689
01:30:12,690 --> 01:30:19,710
He helped her out of the sleigh, and took
her by the hand towards the sled. They both

690
01:30:19,710 --> 01:30:24,830
sat down on it, with Mattie in front and Ethan
behind.

691
01:30:24,830 --> 01:30:30,970
'It's so dark, Ethan. Are you sure you can
see?'

692
01:30:30,970 --> 01:30:39,880
'Oh, I can do this with my eyes closed!' he
laughed. She laughed with him, then after

693
01:30:39,880 --> 01:30:49,550
a moment, he cried: 'Now!' They started off,
and soon the sled was flying down the slope,

694
01:30:49,550 --> 01:30:56,990
round the corner by the big tree, and down
the second slope. They came to a stop, picked

695
01:30:56,990 --> 01:31:01,840
up the sled, and began to climb up the hill
again.

696
01:31:01,840 --> 01:31:05,950
'It was wonderful!' laughed Mattie.

697
01:31:05,950 --> 01:31:10,270
'Weren't you afraid when we went round the
tree?'

698
01:31:10,270 --> 01:31:14,170
'I'm never afraid with you,' she replied.

699
01:31:14,170 --> 01:31:22,700
A deep silence seemed to fall from the starless
sky. At each step of their climb, Ethan said

700
01:31:22,700 --> 01:31:29,740
to himself: 'If's the last time we'll ever
walk together.'

701
01:31:29,740 --> 01:31:36,700
When they reached the Varnum trees, Ethan
put back the sled. 'I guess this must be Ned

702
01:31:36,700 --> 01:31:39,630
Hale's sled,' he said.

703
01:31:39,630 --> 01:31:49,670
'Is this where Ned and Ruth kissed each other?'
Mattie whispered throwing her arms round Ethan.

704
01:31:49,670 --> 01:31:55,510
Her lips found his, and Ethan held her close
to him.

705
01:31:55,510 --> 01:32:04,140
'Goodbye - goodbye,' she said in a shaking
voice, and kissed him again.

706
01:32:04,140 --> 01:32:15,070
'Matt, I can't let you go! What'll we do?
What'll we do?' They stood holding hands like

707
01:32:15,070 --> 01:32:21,020
children. Through the stillness, they heard
the church clock.

708
01:32:21,020 --> 01:32:27,770
'Oh, Ethan, it's already five o'clock. It's
time!'

709
01:32:27,770 --> 01:32:37,620
'Time for what? I'm not leaving you now. How
can we go anywhere without each other, after

710
01:32:37,620 --> 01:32:38,740
this?'

711
01:32:38,740 --> 01:32:47,450
Suddenly she threw her arms round his neck
again. 'Ethan! Ethan! I want you to take me

712
01:32:47,450 --> 01:32:49,070
down again!'

713
01:32:49,070 --> 01:32:51,680
'Down where?'

714
01:32:51,680 --> 01:33:00,650
'Down there. Into the tree, to finish it all.
Then we'll never have to leave each other

715
01:33:00,650 --> 01:33:02,790
again.'

716
01:33:02,790 --> 01:33:10,160
'Matt! What are you saying? Are you crazy?'

717
01:33:10,160 --> 01:33:20,900
'No, but I will be crazy if I leave you. Where'll
I go without you? You're the only person who's

718
01:33:20,900 --> 01:33:29,340
ever been good to me. And there'll be a strange
girl sleeping in my bed where I used to lie

719
01:33:29,340 --> 01:33:35,130
at night and think of you...'

720
01:33:35,130 --> 01:33:43,640
Her words were like pieces torn from his heart.
Now at last he knew that Mattie's feelings

721
01:33:43,640 --> 01:33:51,150
were as strong as his. How could he go back
to that hated house, to the woman who was

722
01:33:51,150 --> 01:33:54,490
waiting for him there?

723
01:33:54,490 --> 01:34:02,340
He held her close and kissed her, but when
her face touched his, it was cold and wet

724
01:34:02,340 --> 01:34:12,660
with tears. He saw the road down to the station,
and through the still air, he heard a train.

725
01:34:12,660 --> 01:34:21,630
The dark trees covered them in blackness and
silence, like a grave. 'Perhaps it'll be like

726
01:34:21,630 --> 01:34:29,620
this,' he thought. 'After this I won't feel
anything.'

727
01:34:29,620 --> 01:34:38,040
'Come,' she whispered, pulling at his hand.
He picked the sled up, and they took their

728
01:34:38,040 --> 01:34:47,940
places on it. This time he made her sit behind
him. She put her arms round him, and he turned

729
01:34:47,940 --> 01:34:57,530
his head and kissed her. She was right - this
was better than being apart.

730
01:34:57,530 --> 01:35:05,239
Just as they started, he heard his horse whinny.
First came the steep drop, and they seemed

731
01:35:05,239 --> 01:35:13,841
to be flying through the air, high up into
the cloudy night. Then Ethan saw the big tree

732
01:35:13,841 --> 01:35:22,090
at the corner of the road, and he said between
his teeth: 'We can do it; I know we can do

733
01:35:22,090 --> 01:35:23,750
it -'

734
01:35:23,750 --> 01:35:30,310
As they flew towards the tree, Mattie held
him closer and he seemed to feel her heart

735
01:35:30,310 --> 01:35:41,450
beating. The tree became bigger and nearer.
'It's waiting for us; it knows,' he thought.

736
01:35:41,450 --> 01:35:49,960
But suddenly his wife's face, grim and twisted,
appeared before him, and he moved to push

737
01:35:49,960 --> 01:35:57,380
the picture away. There was a last moment
when the air shot past him like millions of

738
01:35:57,380 --> 01:36:05,380
burning stars. And then the tree...

739
01:36:05,380 --> 01:36:14,610
The sky was still cloudy, but when he looked
straight up he saw a single star. What was

740
01:36:14,610 --> 01:36:24,320
its name? He used to know, but he couldn't
remember. He felt so tired... Through the

741
01:36:24,320 --> 01:36:33,410
deep stillness, he heard a little animal making
a small, frightened sound. He knew the animal

742
01:36:33,410 --> 01:36:41,380
was in terrible pain - he could feel its pain
shooting through his own body. He reached

743
01:36:41,380 --> 01:36:49,650
out his left arm to help the poor animal,
and felt something soft under his hand. He

744
01:36:49,650 --> 01:36:58,290
tried to move but could not, because there
was a rock, or some heavy thing, lying on

745
01:36:58,290 --> 01:37:08,530
him. Then he realized that his hand was on
Mattie's face, and the sound was coming from

746
01:37:08,530 --> 01:37:11,530
her lips...

747
01:37:11,530 --> 01:37:20,950
He put his face next to hers, and in the darkness,
he saw her eyes open and heard her say his

748
01:37:20,950 --> 01:37:22,640
name.

749
01:37:22,640 --> 01:37:36,150
'Oh, Matt, I thought we'd done it,' he whispered;
and far away, up the hill, he heard the horse

750
01:37:36,150 --> 01:37:57,860
whinny, and thought: 'I ought to give him
his supper...'

751
01:37:57,860 --> 01:38:00,310
CHAPTER EIGHT

752
01:38:00,310 --> 01:38:02,970
Endings

753
01:38:02,970 --> 01:38:10,610
The whining voice stopped as I stepped into
Frome's kitchen. There were two women sitting

754
01:38:10,610 --> 01:38:17,110
there, and I could not tell which one had
been the speaker.

755
01:38:17,110 --> 01:38:23,350
One of them stood up when we entered, and
without a word went to bring a dish of food

756
01:38:23,350 --> 01:38:32,380
to the table. She was tall and thin, and wore
an untidy, shapeless dress. Her lined face

757
01:38:32,380 --> 01:38:40,320
and thin lips were of the same yellowish colour,
and she had thin grey hair and grey, lifeless

758
01:38:40,320 --> 01:38:42,720
eyes.

759
01:38:42,720 --> 01:38:51,430
The other woman was smaller, and she also
had grey hair and a thin, bloodless face.

760
01:38:51,430 --> 01:38:59,300
She turned her head towards me quickly, but
her body did not move at all. Her dark eyes

761
01:38:59,300 --> 01:39:07,380
shone with the crazy brightness that is sometimes
seen in people with disease of the spine.

762
01:39:07,380 --> 01:39:15,200
The kitchen was a poor place. The few pieces
of furniture were of the poorest kind, mostly

763
01:39:15,200 --> 01:39:18,090
broken and dirty.

764
01:39:18,090 --> 01:39:25,400
'My, it's cold in here,' said Frome, looking
around.

765
01:39:25,400 --> 01:39:33,320
The tall woman said nothing, but the dark-eyed
woman answered complainingly, in a thin, whining

766
01:39:33,320 --> 01:39:34,550
voice:

767
01:39:34,550 --> 01:39:43,300
'It's Zeena's fault. She fell asleep and the
fire went out. I've been so cold, waiting

768
01:39:43,300 --> 01:39:46,720
for her to wake up.'

769
01:39:46,720 --> 01:39:52,410
I knew then that it was her voice that I had
heard.

770
01:39:52,410 --> 01:40:00,900
The tall woman brought the food to the table.
Frome looked at me and said: 'This is my wife,

771
01:40:00,900 --> 01:40:09,760
Mrs Frome.' After a moment, he added, turning
to the figure in the armchair: 'And this is

772
01:40:09,760 --> 01:40:14,680
Miss Mattie Silver...

773
01:40:14,680 --> 01:40:21,360
Ruth Hale was very pleased to see me return
safely in the morning, and most surprised

774
01:40:21,360 --> 01:40:24,960
to hear how I had spent the night.

775
01:40:24,960 --> 01:40:33,400
'You must be the first stranger there in twenty
years,' she said. 'It's awful to see them,

776
01:40:33,400 --> 01:40:42,271
all locked up together in that house. And
they're not easy people, any of them. Mattie

777
01:40:42,271 --> 01:40:52,660
used to be; before the accident, she was a
really sweet girl. But not now - she's had

778
01:40:52,660 --> 01:41:02,430
too much pain. Now, when she and Zeena fight,
the look on Ethan's face is enough to break

779
01:41:02,430 --> 01:41:04,580
your heart.'

780
01:41:04,580 --> 01:41:10,310
'Yes, it must be awful for them,' I agreed.

781
01:41:10,310 --> 01:41:17,970
'It was just terrible at the beginning,' she
went on. 'They brought Mattie here, and I

782
01:41:17,970 --> 01:41:27,720
stayed with her all night. Then in the morning,
she opened her eyes and said... Oh, I don't

783
01:41:27,720 --> 01:41:34,700
know why I'm telling you this...' She stopped,
crying.

784
01:41:34,700 --> 01:41:41,780
After a few moments, she dried her tears and
continued: 'Then when the doctors said we

785
01:41:41,780 --> 01:41:49,130
could move Mattie, Zeena sent for her and
took her back to the farm.'

786
01:41:49,130 --> 01:41:54,050
'And she's been there ever since?' I asked.

787
01:41:54,050 --> 01:42:02,550
There was no other place for her to go,' Ruth
Hale answered simply; and I thought how hard

788
01:42:02,550 --> 01:42:05,800
life was for the poor.

789
01:42:05,800 --> 01:42:14,320
'Zeena's cared for the pair of them for over
twenty years now,' Ruth Hale went on. 'And

790
01:42:14,320 --> 01:42:20,650
there they all are, shut up in that one kitchen.'

791
01:42:20,650 --> 01:42:25,760
Then she looked at me and said in a low voice:

792
01:42:25,760 --> 01:42:33,140
There was one day, about a week after the
accident, when they thought Mattie couldn't

793
01:42:33,140 --> 01:42:45,330
live. Well, I say it was a pity she did. People
think that's an awful thing to say, but they

794
01:42:45,330 --> 01:42:54,000
weren't with her when she first woke up...
And I say this, too. All those years with

795
01:42:54,000 --> 01:43:03,500
Mattie have destroyed Ethan. The way they
are now, there's not much difference between

796
01:43:03,500 --> 01:43:13,330
the Fromes up at the farm and the Fromes down
in their graves - except that down there they're

797
01:43:13,330 --> 01:43:24,090
all silent and the women have to keep quiet.'

798
01:43:24,090 --> 01:43:37,980
- THE END -

